	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		"I.  Hate.  This.  Assignment." I said as I smacked my forehead into the table.<br/><br/>"Whoa, whoa there big guy.  You're going to spill my beer.  So what did Jose tell you?" Scrap asked as he grasped his beer glass with both hands, coddling it as if to prevent losing a drop of the hoppy, golden contents.<br/>"Jose gave me some names, but I'm not sure if I quite understand the tale he was weaving on the phone." I said as I scratched my frazzled hair with a monkey paw.<br/><br/>"Spill it." Scrap demanded as he lit a cigarette.<br/><br/>"According to our little insider, there are two employees primarily involved.  Both of the employees are processors, however one has somehow come into possession of a destroyer's key.  This is clearly against company policy and completely undermines the established chain of custody procedure." I said in disbelief.<br/><br/>"Nice." Scrap said as he sipped his beer.<br/><br/>"Oh wait, it gets better! The bar scanner that the processors use to check the boxes in and out of the facility displays the customer name.  The processors stack certain company boxes in a specific place.  The other boxes are placed into the storage rooms in their inventoried places.  The remaining boxes are placed on a morning truck by the processors.  One of the processors is an 'early bird' and gets to work before the others.  He meets the driver on the dock, unlocks the truck, unlocks the boxes, locks the truck and the driver drives away!" I exclaimed.<br/><br/>"No.  Way." Scrap said as he accidentally extinguished his cigarette in his beer instead of the ashtray.  "Dammit!  I hate it when I do that.  So what happens to the boxes after they leave the facility?" <br/><br/>I thought for a moment, trying to recollect everything that Jose had shared with me in our phone conversation.<br/><br/>"The driver makes a stop at the other processor's house and unloads the tapes out of the boxes.  The tapes are placed into cardboard boxes in the other processor's garage.  The driver then makes his other stops for the day and returns with the boxes.  The boxes go directly from the truck back into the storage rooms." I said.<br/><br/>"Wait a second.  So the inventory controller, Jose, is marking these as being 'en route' which is Allison Technology language for 'still on the truck'.  This way they don't appear 'unaccountable', right? Friggin' smooth." Scrap said with a loud belch.<br/><br/>"Exactly.  Jose didn't have a lot of the details that I was really looking for, but we do have some leads to go on now." I replied.<br/><br/>"Why do I get the feeling we'll be snooping around Allison Technologies tomorrow to build this case?" Scrap moaned.<br/><br/>The next morning, Scrap and I returned to Allison Technologies and arranged a short meeting with the office manager, Janelle. Jose was only able to give me first names, which I assumed was because of intimidation or he really didn't know. <br/><br/>Jonathan had given us carte blanche access to company records, so Janelle sat us down in front of a workstation and access to their employee records system.  Ironically, the very software I was navigating through was the same software that Allison had removed from the market years ago.<br/><br/>I searched for all current employees with a first name of "Tomas", which returned a single record: Tomas Tomason.  Tomas had been with the company since the "software days" as Jonathan referred to them.  I added the Tomason record to the print queue and proceeded with my next search: Jeffry.  A single record was returned.<br/><br/>"Oh this just gets better and better." I said as I laid my head on the desk.<br/><br/>"What now?  What's the dude's name?" Scrap asked as he maneuvered behind me for a better look.<br/><br/>Jeffry Allison.<p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
